@JA-ti3wd Well actually most people do think that fossil fuels come from fossils, that is how it is presented to the uneducated public. This also invokes the idea that hydrocarbons are a finite resource that should be rationed, priced and taxed (carbon tax).

Guess what happens when you increase heat into a cold climate. It gets warmer, the trees and plants increase and have a longer growth cycle. Temperatures have not risen by any significant amounts. The sun cycle of 10+/- years has more to do with weather change than any other influential factors. The frequency zone, which the Earth is in around the sun, only varies minimally. The impact from an outside force has, in the past, shifted the Earth to far extremes within this zone, but the Earth has and will always remain within this frequency zone, just as the moon will always remain within its frequency zone around the Earth. 

One more thing, these hydrocarbons did not leave the carbon cycle millions of years ago, what do you suppose a volcano does? When the Earth's temperature rises to a point it cools itself by volcanic eruptions. Imagine the release of hydrocarbons, directly injected into the atmosphere, the Earth would be cooled down significantly by the extra water vapor creating massive ice caps across the northern and southern regions (LIA).

